The first virtual provider is coming to Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The telecommunications market in Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech suppliers offer practically all the services they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, there is something missing here - a virtual provider who forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe this one won't wait for a long time.
The fact that the Czech mobile telephone providers are working on the most expensive in Europe at all, we have often reported on Mobil.cz.
This also confirmed the telecommunications authority ČTU, which pointed out that the price for a SMS here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the last steps of the European Commission in regulating roaming fees, there is so likely a paradox situation - for some customers of the Czech mobile telephone providers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are prices in Czech Republic so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really makes a fighting response.
Perhaps it sounds paradox, but in Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
On the other hand, mobile telecommunications providers are pleased to shame over the fact that there is extremely much competition in the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who had often said in the past that there was no place for another supplier in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a classic provider with his own network has no more specially many chances (and he would probably hardly find frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual provider.
Just the entry of virtual providers to the mobile market led to a significant reduction in prices, which the classic mobile telephone providers had to respond to.
There were votes similar to those in the United Kingdom before the entry into the market of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile.
However, it has proved that there is room for such providers and that these can really be successful.
Moreover, you do not need to look for examples long.
In February we reported about the start of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just one half year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus rise to the five largest provider of the country.
The Penta financial group, which has U:phone in Czech Republic, is behind Mobiling.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need relatively high costs for the construction, operation and entertainment of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually profile themselves as low-cost companies - they offer cheap telephone conversations and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in UK offers SMS at least half the cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good draw to put on a non-scientific target group.
This provider is specifically addressed to men.
"Every guy choose Mobilking - the provider that they like and which they can trust," said David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator company of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a concept similar to that in Poland could be taken into the Czech Republic.
The press speaker of Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offer."
In Czech Republic without chance, the mobile phone providers mean
However, it is almost certain that when a virtual mobile provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobile.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look very hopeful.
It will be more likely to enter the market of Mobilking in other countries of our region," says a telephone conversation for mobile.cz Jana Studničková, press speaker of the Penta financial group.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile telecommunications providers in the Czech Republic are not specially adapted to this thought.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything for no potential competitor.
Your interest in launching a virtual mobile provider has long been showing the GTS Novera group, who wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the business sector.
"We are very interested in offering our customers not only fixed networks but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this opportunity with all Czech mobile telephone providers.
With some of them we were already able to achieve negotiations," said the press speaker of the Pavel Kaidl Group.
Maybe better times are coming now.
Not official information shows that the first virtual provider may be expected until the end of the year.
But so far this is surrounded by an inconvenient wall of silence.
"In this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full-quality virtual provider in Czech Republic.
The Czech market shows great specificities to other markets.
We have not yet been addressed by any subject with a complex and serious project in this area," says his Declaration for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Srše ́ from the Telefónica O2 press department.
Further suppliers also point to the specificity of the Czech market.
The press speaker of T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds in rare conformity with the O2 statement: "To date we have not found a viable and both sides of advantage that could be built on."
And she adds: "In the network of T-Mobile, hardly a virtual provider will appear until the end of the year.
At this moment we have to have a specific offer to think so short-term."
Vodafone rather focuses on fulfilling the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "For negotiations with potential virtual providers, we are open, especially in the field of sharing costs and infrastructure.
This is exactly what we view from the customers as the best.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area is looking for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet."
The responsible authorities - with the suppliers hand in hand
The operation of mobile telephone providers is easy to understand, another provider called more competition, this would lead to lower prices and thereby also to a decline in profits.
So why should such a competitor be facilitated to enter the market?
That the providers can draw on a string when it comes to something, it also proves the long Hin and Her about the creation of U:fon.
The strongest pressure toward ČTÚ went out from the company T-Mobile at the time U:phone came on the market.
This also demonstrates the publicly available information from the ČTU websites.
But now U:fon is suitable as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competitiveness of the mobile market has recently also been strengthened by the entry into the market by a fourth mobile telephone provider.
Taking into account the character of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would make high demands on the market itself and, above all, on his services."
However, in view of this approach by mobile telephone providers, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is amazed.
It is not only the attitude of the ČTU, which, unfortunately, has no competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic, in contrast to the United Kingdom and other high-developed countries.
It has exclusively the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
This, however, refers to its very typical attitude on this whole problem.
"The entry into the market of a virtual mobile provider would then be possible after the conclusion of a contract between a mobile telephone provider and a virtual provider through the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far no such contract has been concluded because the offer of potential stakeholders is likely not sufficiently interesting for the classic providers," says in his answer to our request Kristián Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS.
Such a formation would not be surprised by representatives of the suppliers.
Of a authority representing consumer interests, and, among other things, to ensure that no one misuses its position on the market, this is more than concernful.
Particularly when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In abroad, where virtual providers work normally, it is necessary to observe that their entry into the market has contributed to a reduction in prices in mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a lower price is likely not part of the interests of the UOHS.
Really shocking in this case is the almost already touching conformity of the three mobile telephone providers, resulting from their reactions.
The question is whether it is really just a coincidence.
Just as the absolutely same petrol price at the tank stations is surely only coincidence and the result of a hard competition.
"The Authority has not discovered any signs of competition, and therefore it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the suppliers have a dominant market position, so he does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for his trade on the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile market for virtual providers are probably also missing by the regulatory authority for telecommunications," Chalupa stated in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, developed by the ČTU, after telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile telephone providers have a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different viewpoint - for the entry into the market of a virtual provider always requires the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile phone provider has - logically - the monopolie for his network.
It means that it necessarily takes a dominant position in a certain segment.
However, even if you do not take part in this argument, it should be a warning for the UOHS that three mobile telephone providers are considerably similar.
In this respect, complaints of a number of stakeholders (including the GTS Novera company mentioned above) show that they are facing very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The resolution of responsibility to the ČTU is then a very common trick in telecommunications services, which distinguishes the ÚOHS from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted Novelle of the Telecommunications Act has not succeeded in extending the competences of ČTU in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts have promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS need to know that too well, but they are likely to have other interests.
It's okay if no one looks at.
Unrespected remains the functioning of any pseudovirtual provider of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies who issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but which are only partially public.
It is normally companies operating in multilevel marketing.
For example, own mobile telephone services offer Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies are usually only selected.
The joke of the matter is that the company acts as a classical company that orders a large amount of SIM cards to the operator.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the conditions of use of all Czech mobile telecommunications providers prohibit a similar retail sale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it may be a violation of the contractual conditions with which we will be discussed, which can lead to the end of cooperation with the corresponding society," answered Martina Kemrová on our question on this issue.
It is, however, quite unlikely that such a thing is not true with the person responsible for the mobile telecommunications providers.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator is opposed to such action.
The activities of these companies do not lead to negligible profits, at the same time, they are not affected by the actual official marketing, unlike the actual virtual providers.
Miroslav Čepický recalls potential problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, although the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run on their names, so they cannot fully have such information as the normal customers of mobile telephone providers."
But the ČTU would have to be at least strange.
There is also another question for the UOHS.
The mobile telephone providers close their eyes before such a procedure, why are they locking up against a virtual provider?
It is added that the UOHS has quite strong competences to discover such activities, and if it does not want it, it does not have to satisfy the declaration of the suppliers, they don't know about it, and their conditions would prohibit it.
When Czech Republic is no longer expensive
As the text has already emphasized several times, the entry into the market of virtual providers led to a significant decrease in prices in the various services.
In practically all countries where virtual providers have been created, classical providers have tried to prevent their creation almost more or less.
The arguments used by them were practically identical - a small, or too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the high-developed countries, however, in these moments, the regulatory bodies acted, which did not even try to preserve the interests of mobile telephone providers, but who tried to preserve their customers.
If it was by formal measures or by non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created and followed further.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing into the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experiences, we cannot disclose the impression that unclearness in the competences in these cases is more than favourable.
But we don't throw the flint into the grain.
If the background information is true and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile market may soon move back.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile provider, the UOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting other stakeholders (discrimination).
And the Czechs will not finally call more expensive than the rest of Europe.
