Hepatitis: When to visit your doctor?
Worldwide, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed under the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people is estimated to be a hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and yellowness are frequent, but the inflammation and the diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the disease, the hepatitis viruses are spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. by contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted by blood and other body liquids (e.g. sperm, discharge or spray).
Travelers are recommended for vaccination against virus A and B, at least there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A are shown approximately two-three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by illness, weakness, abdominal pain and breast-feeding.
After that, the yellowness appears on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine dark, and the healing may last for up to two or three weeks.
Over the world, approximately 1 million people die every year on the far more severe diseases caused by hepatitis B such as liver cancer and hepatic cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that only every tenth infected in medicine treatment is estimated.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: untreated can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the infector degrades the liver cells dullly - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular checks, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease occurs more frequently: those who received a blood transfusion before 1991, drug-dependent, and tatovered.
At present, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated to be 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the home doctor in the first signs of unknown origin.
Timely detected, the disease is healable, the virus can be eradicated, thus banning the risk of infection and preventing the formation of cancer.
On September 30, the world day of hepatitis, 2004, is the first time organised by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to strengthen consciousness of this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their development and the importance of early detection.
